WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.160 --> 00:00:03.520
Hello everyone, today we are going to&nbsp;
start a new adventure in gregtech 6.

00:00:03.520 --> 00:00:08.160
as we look around, we notice some surface rocks&nbsp;
which we can collect and use to craft our first&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:08.160 --> 00:00:13.440
axe. which can be crafted witouth crafting table.
this axe is cheap and capable of chopping down&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:13.440 --> 00:00:16.880
multiple logs at once, but it's&nbsp;
slow and it has a low durability.&nbsp;

00:00:16.880 --> 00:00:20.000
but that's also because we made&nbsp;
this axe out of marble pebbles.&nbsp;

00:00:20.000 --> 00:00:23.400
and if we look around a little bit more,&nbsp;
we can indeed find some better rocks.&nbsp;

00:00:23.400 --> 00:00:28.800
and after spending enough time collecting rocks,&nbsp;
we figured out that red granite is the best one.&nbsp;

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:33.440
tools made out of this rock can even harvest&nbsp;
obsidian, but the speed isn't that good and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:33.440 --> 00:00:37.040
sicne those tools are still made out of&nbsp;
pebbles, the durability is quite low.&nbsp;

00:00:37.040 --> 00:00:39.440
but that's not much of a big&nbsp;
deal, since we can just look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:39.440 --> 00:00:44.080
around pebbles to find more of that material.
once we locate the solid rock, we just have to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:48.240
break the stone twice with a hammer to obtain&nbsp;
all of the pebbles we could possibly need.&nbsp;

00:00:48.240 --> 00:00:52.960
to get better tools we will want to process some&nbsp;
metals, but first we will be looking for a nice&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:57.600
place where we can start building our industry.
since we might need chlorine in the future,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:57.600 --> 00:01:02.400
setting by the seaside is probably a good idea.
and that totally wasn't an excuse so we could have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:02.400 --> 00:01:07.040
a nice sea house with view on the sun set.
and after all of that work, we can finally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:11.200
rest a little bit while eating some&nbsp;
sweet berries we found on our way.&nbsp;

00:01:11.200 --> 00:01:15.280
and that's when we found out that&nbsp;
eating too many sweets isn't healty.&nbsp;

00:01:15.280 --> 00:01:19.360
the next day we decided to start working&nbsp;
on a proper garden to fix our diet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:19.360 --> 00:01:24.320
but after removing some rocks we figured out there&nbsp;
was a high concentration of copper in our soil.&nbsp;

00:01:24.320 --> 00:01:29.120
we started digging deeper to investigate, and we&nbsp;
eventually found more and more copper-rich rocks.&nbsp;

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:32.560
but copper on it's own is&nbsp;
an awful material for tools.&nbsp;

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:36.960
to make it stronger we have to add some&nbsp;
of the tin we also found in our backyard.&nbsp;

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:41.760
but to properly alloy together those two&nbsp;
metals, we have to heat up the mixture at 1400K.&nbsp;

00:01:42.960 --> 00:01:47.040
that has do be done inside a crucible,&nbsp;
which we can easily craft with some clay.&nbsp;

00:01:47.040 --> 00:01:50.880
to heat it up, we turn on a burning&nbsp;
box underneath the crucible.&nbsp;

00:01:50.880 --> 00:01:54.960
now we just have to throw the raw ingredients&nbsp;
in and wait for everything to melt.&nbsp;

00:01:54.960 --> 00:02:00.160
once the mixture turned the right color and we&nbsp;
can pour out the molten petal into a pickaxe mold.&nbsp;

00:02:00.160 --> 00:02:03.920
to celebrate the advent of bronze age,&nbsp;
we can make a jumbo sandwich which we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.920 --> 00:02:06.960
can eat in a single bite.
and that's how long it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.960 --> 00:02:11.440
took for our crucible to turn yellow.
and before we could even finish that phrase,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.440 --> 00:02:14.560
the crucible melted.
indeed, in gregtech 6,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:18.160
everything has a melting point.
how quickly we reach that temperature&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:18.160 --> 00:02:23.440
depends on the thermal mass we are trying to heat&nbsp;
up and how much ehat energy we add to the thing.&nbsp;

00:02:23.440 --> 00:02:27.120
while we can guess the current temperature&nbsp;
just by looking at the color of the crucible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:27.120 --> 00:02:31.600
a better way is to craft a thermometer.
to craft it , we will need some mercury,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:31.600 --> 00:02:36.480
so we adventured in search of new minerals.
during our exploration, we found huge deposits&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.480 --> 00:02:42.000
of coal and huge deposits of iron-rich sand
underground we found all sorts of ores,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.280
some of which were rather hard to notice.
we also found a weird building.&nbsp;

00:02:47.280 --> 00:02:52.080
once inside, it turned out to be an abandoned&nbsp;
base stocked with many different chemicals and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:52.080 --> 00:02:56.000
a huge amount of all sorts of metals.
we even found already worked metal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.000 --> 00:02:59.360
parts in some nearby drawers.
and as if all of those goodies&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:03.920
weren't enough, we even found the holy&nbsp;
grail of the bronze age: a lighter.&nbsp;

00:03:03.920 --> 00:03:08.720
this one has a 100% success rate, and we&nbsp;
even have some spare propane to refill it.&nbsp;

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:13.920
and while we found mercury in this place, we still&nbsp;
explored more areas to secure a proper source.&nbsp;

00:03:13.920 --> 00:03:17.920
we crossed multiple dimensions, until&nbsp;
we finally found a redstone vein, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:17.920 --> 00:03:24.160
also contains cinnabar, a mercury-rich metal.
we processed the raw ore to increase the yield,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:24.160 --> 00:03:28.640
finally heated it up to extract&nbsp;
some mercury for our thermometer.&nbsp;

00:03:28.640 --> 00:03:35.520
with this, we can finally measure temperature&nbsp;
more precisely, easing the metal alloying process.&nbsp;

00:03:35.520 --> 00:03:39.200
the next step was to connect our&nbsp;
thermometer to a redstone sensor,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.200 --> 00:03:44.080
allowing us to automate metal alloying.
to do so, we first configure our new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:44.080 --> 00:03:47.440
digital thermometer with the correct&nbsp;
temperature, then we connect it to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:52.400
molds and enable out output on redstone.
next we configure a pair of hoppers with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:52.400 --> 00:03:55.840
the correct input ratio, and to&nbsp;
avoid overfilling our crucible,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:55.840 --> 00:04:00.400
we use a properly configured weight sensor
and this simple system can easily be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.400 --> 00:04:04.480
expanded to allow for more complex&nbsp;
alloys, such as stainless steel.&nbsp;

00:04:04.480 --> 00:04:08.320
while this has many usages, we are&nbsp;
also going to need some normal steel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.320 --> 00:04:12.560
which is made by pumping air in a crucible.
to do so, we will have to input kinetic&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.560 --> 00:04:17.600
energy to the crucible. we can do that&nbsp;
by vibrating it using a steam engine.&nbsp;

00:04:17.600 --> 00:04:21.840
running this machine will require some steam,&nbsp;
which we can produce by boiling water inside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.840 --> 00:04:27.360
some boilers, which we heat up using the same&nbsp;
burning boxes we can use to heat up crucibles.&nbsp;

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:32.240
now that we managed to obtain steels we can do&nbsp;
many things, starting from a bigger crucible.&nbsp;

00:04:32.240 --> 00:04:36.720
this one will be able to fit multiple blocks&nbsp;
of material, easing the melting process.&nbsp;

00:04:36.720 --> 00:04:40.640
and the reason why we have minerals&nbsp;
in the form of cubic meter-sized dust&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:40.640 --> 00:04:44.480
is our new ore processing plant
the first step is to run our raw&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:48.480
ores in a crusher, which will break&nbsp;
the big rocks into smaller chunks.&nbsp;

00:04:48.480 --> 00:04:53.280
then we run those crushed rocks in a sluice to&nbsp;
separate the stone from the actual minerals.&nbsp;

00:04:53.280 --> 00:04:57.360
next we run the purified ores through a&nbsp;
centrifuge to filter out more byproducts.&nbsp;

00:04:57.360 --> 00:05:02.640
finally, we macerate all of the centrifuged ores&nbsp;
in a shredder to get everything in dust form.&nbsp;

00:05:02.640 --> 00:05:08.320
however, those dusts won't all have the same size.
to properly sort out all of those dust,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:08.320 --> 00:05:12.240
we use a system of hoppers and funnels to&nbsp;
first cluster all of the dusts into small&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:15.840
size and then into full blocks.
while most of those can be melted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:15.840 --> 00:05:20.080
into pure metal using a crucible,&nbsp;
others require some extra refinement.&nbsp;

00:05:20.080 --> 00:05:24.400
so we built some ore-specific processing&nbsp;
lines, like this one for aluminum.&nbsp;

00:05:24.400 --> 00:05:29.200
to obtain this MV material we had to use an&nbsp;
electrolyzer, and you may be wondering why we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:29.200 --> 00:05:33.760
aren't using electricity for other setups.
well, there are two main reasons.&nbsp;

00:05:33.760 --> 00:05:37.440
the first one is the horrible&nbsp;
efficiency of transforming energy.&nbsp;

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:40.960
and here i really want to be pedantic&nbsp;
on what i mean with energy loss.&nbsp;

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:46.160
we start with a 25% loss when burning materials&nbsp;
to produce the heat units required to boil water.&nbsp;

00:05:46.160 --> 00:05:50.880
then, a boiler will convert that heat&nbsp;
into steam. if we use distilled water,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.880 --> 00:05:55.040
this process will be perfectly efficient.
we pipe the steam to a turbine,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:55.040 --> 00:05:59.680
which will dissipate 1/3 of the energy&nbsp;
while using the hot gas to spin a rotor.&nbsp;

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:03.360
this will produce rotation units,&nbsp;
which we shaft to a dynamo.&nbsp;

00:06:03.360 --> 00:06:08.800
here, after losing almost one more third of our&nbsp;
energy to friction, we finally get electricity.&nbsp;

00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:12.160
then we have the usual cable&nbsp;
loss, which here is negligible.&nbsp;

00:06:12.160 --> 00:06:15.600
and after losing more than half of the&nbsp;
starting energy, we figured out that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:15.600 --> 00:06:19.760
most machines don't use electricity.
so have to deal with losing an other&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:19.760 --> 00:06:24.480
half of our electric energy to convert&nbsp;
it back to whatever we actually needed.&nbsp;

00:06:24.480 --> 00:06:29.680
the second issue is that, right now, we can only&nbsp;
shut off machines by cutting the power feed.&nbsp;

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:33.520
so, if we want to have the comforts of&nbsp;
electricity versatility for machines that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.520 --> 00:06:39.040
don't require too much power, we will want some&nbsp;
machine switch covers and also some battery boxes.&nbsp;

00:06:39.040 --> 00:06:43.040
however, both of those things will require&nbsp;
some circuits, and even the lowest tier of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:43.040 --> 00:06:47.600
circuit requires plastic and silicon boules.
while the main issue of silicon is a bit of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:47.600 --> 00:06:53.280
inert gas and processing time, making plastic has&nbsp;
a mandatory titanium tetrachloride requirement&nbsp;

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:57.520
since we needed just a few drops, we manually&nbsp;
handled all sorts of chemicals to process some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:57.520 --> 00:07:02.160
of the bauxite leftovers into titanium.
chemical reactors aren't a thing here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.160 --> 00:07:05.600
so we had to deal with all sort&nbsp;
of never-seen-before machines&nbsp;

00:07:05.600 --> 00:07:10.720
and after carefully measuring the correct amount&nbsp;
of ingredients, we made our first plastic.&nbsp;

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:14.960
with that we had every required ingredient,&nbsp;
so we proceeded into quickly working&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.960 --> 00:07:19.280
everything into our first electric circuit.
we used those to craft some machine switch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.280 --> 00:07:22.400
covers, and then we proceeded&nbsp;
into building our LV workshop.&nbsp;

00:07:22.400 --> 00:07:26.720
and since some machines don't have an&nbsp;
integrated motor, we still use some bronze&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:26.720 --> 00:07:31.680
machines powered by a dedicated electric motor.
we have already seen how inefficient that is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:31.680 --> 00:07:34.800
but being able to instantly start&nbsp;
and stop those engines from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:34.800 --> 00:07:40.400
batteries is really nice qol improvement.
also, there are some new forms of energy we can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:40.400 --> 00:07:46.480
derive from electriciy, such as magnetic units,&nbsp;
made from an electromagnet to power polarizers&nbsp;

00:07:46.480 --> 00:07:52.560
and laser units, made by a CO2 laser, which will&nbsp;
have many usages in the future, but for now we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:52.560 --> 00:07:58.080
can use that for a laser engrave so that we can&nbsp;
make LuV circuits, the highest tier available.&nbsp;

00:07:58.080 --> 00:08:02.000
with those we unlocked all sorts of cool&nbsp;
things, and our first objective is going to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:02.000 --> 00:08:06.880
a nuclear reactor to fix our energy production.
to get started, we are going to fuel it using&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:06.880 --> 00:08:12.320
uranium 238, which is super cheap and&nbsp;
will keep producing heat for 800 hours.&nbsp;

00:08:12.320 --> 00:08:16.880
in this setup, we are using some ic2 coolant&nbsp;
to get the heat out of the reactor and bring&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:21.760
it to some heat exchangers, where, as&nbsp;
usual, we boil water to spin a turbine.&nbsp;

00:08:21.760 --> 00:08:26.320
and this time, to avoid using expensive cables&nbsp;
that will also lose power, we made a long shaft&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:26.320 --> 00:08:31.600
to our base, where we have a small dynamo that&nbsp;
slowly charges up our huge batteries already&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:36.720
sized for a bigger setup we will eventually build.
the first thing we will be using out new power&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.720 --> 00:08:41.600
source for is a thermoelectric cooler to run our&nbsp;
new cryogenic distillation tower to obtain some&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:41.600 --> 00:08:45.840
noble gasses for a nanoscale fabricator,&nbsp;
used to make graphene parts, which have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:50.640
incredible stats despite begin super cheap.
notably, we can now make carbon crucibles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:50.640 --> 00:08:55.360
capable of handling even the toughest materials.
we are going to heat it up with our new electric&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:55.360 --> 00:09:00.800
heater, which perfectly manages temperature.
and what we just made is tungsten carbide,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:00.800 --> 00:09:04.800
used to make the better extruder&nbsp;
capable of doing all sorts of jobs.&nbsp;

00:09:04.800 --> 00:09:08.240
however, all of those new machines&nbsp;
quickly drained our battery buffer.&nbsp;

00:09:08.240 --> 00:09:12.320
it was clear we needed a bigger nuclear&nbsp;
reactor, and to speed up the crafting process,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:12.320 --> 00:09:17.440
we increased our efficiency by directly connecting&nbsp;
our heaviest machinery to our old nuclear reactor.&nbsp;

00:09:17.440 --> 00:09:22.080
and after a lot of dense plates, we&nbsp;
finally completed our new reactor plant.&nbsp;

00:09:22.080 --> 00:09:26.800
this time we are using 6 reactor cores filled&nbsp;
with a mix of different rods achieving a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:26.800 --> 00:09:31.920
production over 9000 heat units per tick.
we use some of that heat to keep the water&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:31.920 --> 00:09:35.760
loop going and the rest goes into&nbsp;
heating two large invar boilers.&nbsp;

00:09:35.760 --> 00:09:39.920
those will produce 16k liters of&nbsp;
steam per tick, which we use to spin&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:39.920 --> 00:09:45.600
a large turbine with an output of 5k ru/t
finally, a large dynamo will convert that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:45.600 --> 00:09:50.880
into 4k eu/t, just below the Iv threshold.
the reason why the output isn't consistent&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:55.040
is that we aren't using that energy and the&nbsp;
batteries in our buffer and fully charged.

